{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a86e02cd-c50c-4a6e-a5ad-88dd1d5d1076","content":"Here's the scan result for **my_app/**:\n\n### Untestable Static Dependencies Found\n\n| File | Line | Call | Risk |\n|------|------|------|------|\n| `views.py` | 3 | `datetime.now()` | 🔴 High — non-deterministic, hard to assert in tests |\n\n**1 static call site found in 1 file.**\n\n### Why it's a problem\n`datetime.now()` is called directly, so tests can't control the returned time. Any assertion on the rendered `time` value will be flaky.\n\n### Recommended fix (Python/Django)\nUse Django's `django.utils.timezone.now` combined with [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) or `unittest.mock.patch` to freeze time in tests:\n\n```python\n# views.py — use Django's timezone-aware helper\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\n```python\n# tests.py — freeze time for deterministic assertions\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-01-01 12:00:00\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    response = self.client.get('/')\n    self.assertContains(response, \"2026-01-01\")\n```\n\nThis is a small project with only one call site, so the fix is quick. Want me to apply it?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd271064-4b67-4b7b-9442-b03942ea805f","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"4C16:1E6FAE:C0289D:E9574F:6A0143F7"},"id":"2e05c7d7-d52e-4c22-ad84-ee427dec3a17","timestamp":"2026-05-11T02:50:41.553Z","parentId":"778c902f-60a5-4351-b0ac-2d87a1a31fec"}
